Tribal rebels attacked a paramilitary convoy in restive southwest Pakistan, killing three soldiers and injuring seven others.
Regular army troops backed by two military helicopters had been sent to tackle the situation.
A fierce gunbattle between paramilitary troops and renegade tribesmen left eight soldiers dead and 23 others wounded in an insurgency-wracked area of southwestern Pakistan.
During the 1970s Baluchistan was the scene of a major uprising which was brutally put down by the government.
Up to 45 people, including eight soldiers, were killed in the clashes between the Frontier Corps troops and Bugti tribesmen, who dominate Dera Bugti.
